==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*kauxaz'', from Indo-European ''*keu-k-'', a suffixed form of ''*keu-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''hāch'', Old Saxon ''hōh'' (Dutch ''[[hoog]]''), Old High German ''[[hōh]]'' (German ''[[hoch]]''), Old Norse ''[[hár]]'', Gothic [[𐌷𐌰𐌿𐌷𐍃]].  The Indo-European root is also the source of Lithuanian [[kaukas]], Russian [[куча]].

